        "# Python Reference for Time Series and Sequence Learning\n",
        "\n",
        "This appendix collects the Python patterns used throughout the book.  It is designed as a practical companion for the labs.  The goal is not to replace documentation for `numpy`, `pandas`, `statsmodels`, `scikit-learn`, `torch`, or `plotly`, but to give students a consistent workflow for simulation, visualization, modeling, validation, and debugging.\n",
        "\n",
        "The guiding principle is simple: in time series, code must respect time order.  Random shuffling, scaling with future data, or using future observations as features can make a model look much better than it really is.\n",
        "\n",
