        "## A.18 AI-assisted Python workflow\n",
        "\n",
        "AI tools are helpful for code review, but they must be asked precise, time-series-aware questions.  Good prompts include the data structure, the forecast horizon, the information set, and the validation design.\n",
        "\n",
        "Example prompt:\n",
        "\n",
        "> I am forecasting $y_{t+12}$ using only information available up to time $t$.  Here is my feature construction and train/test split.  Check whether any feature leaks future information.  Also check whether my scaling is fitted only on the training set.\n",
        "\n",
        "Another useful prompt:\n",
        "\n",
        "> Here is my residual ACF, Ljung-Box result, and rolling-origin error table.  Give three possible reasons the model fails, and propose checks that I can verify with code.\n",
        "\n",
        "AI-generated code should be treated as a draft.  Before using it in a project, verify the following.\n",
        "\n",
        "- The model does not use future observations as predictors.\n",
        "- Differencing, scaling, and feature engineering are performed in the correct chronological order.\n",
        "- The validation method matches the forecasting task.\n",
        "- Baselines are included.\n",
        "- Residual diagnostics are checked.\n",
        "- The code is reproducible from a fresh runtime.\n",
        "\n",
        "## A.19 Minimal project notebook structure\n",
        "\n",
        "A strong final-project notebook should follow this structure.\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Problem statement and forecast contract.\n",
        "2. Data loading and cleaning.\n",
        "3. Exploratory time-series analysis.\n",
        "4. Baseline models.\n",
        "5. Main models.\n",
        "6. Rolling-origin or chronological validation.\n",
        "7. Residual diagnostics and uncertainty.\n",
        "8. Interpretation and limitations.\n",
        "9. Final conclusion.\n",
        "\n",
